&quot;He is a lazy fellow&quot; or &quot;He is lasy&quot;.<br>
&quot;dull blades/blunt swords&quot; or &quot;This sword is blunt/dull&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kagebu>Kagebu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/19/03 9:55:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1098.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://liquid2k.com/datenshidojo/sano01.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Namakura</span><hr size=1> Well, Aoh, you were the one who gave me this term in the first place, though you may not have understood what I was trying to use it for. <br>
Since Namakura is an adjective, I guess I should combine it with another word like &quot;Namakura-Gatana&quot;, but then again, that wouldn't sound right to English readers. I could also just drop the Japanese and go with &quot;blunt sword&quot;, but that just doesn't sound right (or cool enough <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
Any other suggestions that would describe this weapon? (heck, something like &quot;Life saving sword&quot; would be allright, I guess.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/19/03 12:21:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1098.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Namakura</span><hr size=1> hey kagebu, are you writing this novel in english?  Cuz' if that's the case, then i wouldn't see a problem with naming the sword &quot;namakura&quot;, even though it's just an adjective (i.e the rest of the novel in english, but like people's names/weapon names/spells etc. in japanese)<br>
<br>
This strikes me as something similar to how the final fantasy games sometimes use names like &quot;masamune&quot; for a sword or &quot;aegis&quot; for an esper, etc. even though this usage isn't exactly proper. (aegis isn't japanese btw, though i assume you know that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
So if you want it to be sort of &quot;cool&quot; I think using namakura as the name for a weapon in an otherwise english novel would be great.  (of course, if you're writing it in japanese then it would just sound weird LOL)<br>
<br>
good luck! <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu. </span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->  </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
